\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
When I went up, I had been heavily politicised at school \endash  not because of school \endash 
 because of my friends, I suppose, because of what was happening in the world, because of Spain and so on, and it was difficult to be neutral about that at the time. So the Spanish War and everything was very important. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Did you think of going there yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab No. No, I never did. I don
\rquote t know why. Yesterday I was having a drink with somebody here, and I met my old friend James Cornford, and [his father] John Cornford was a great hero of CUSC [Cambridge
 University Socialist Club] when I came up. In fact I remember, there was a sort of shrine to him at the end of the Socialist Club Meeting Room which was very impressive. No, I never thought of going there \endash  I don\rquote 
t know why. Well, partly because I was having a great struggle in myself between pacifism and some more active resistance. Because I had an aunt \endash  well, she wasn\rquote t really an aunt, she was a friend of my mother\rquote s \endash 
 they were in the Post Office together \endash  she also came from the North of Scotland, right up North by Dounreay. And she was a follower of Gandhi, and a vegetarian, and a pacifist, who took me to lunch, I can remember, at Heal\rquote 
s in Tottenham Court Road, because they had a vegetarian part of the restaurant, or menu, there. So I was much impre
ssed by her, and by the whole of the Pacifist Movement. So it was a great struggle for me with Spain, as the whole problem of arms for Spain was whether that was the best thing or not. I suppose it was partly Guernica that resolved my doubts about that.

\par 
