\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, I know, but I
\rquote d love to hear a bit more about it. So I was thinking maybe we could come back to that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, of course. Of course.

\par 
\par [BREAK IN RECORDING]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab So let\rquote 
s go back, then, to 1939, when you were in Cambridge, and War breaks out. Can you tell me the story of what happens then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, I was up at Cambridge. War broke out in, what, August, was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And I was then climbing, with my brother, up in the Isle of Skye \endash  no, further up the West Coast of Scotland. I told you I\rquote d been with Arnold Kettle and others, and George Scurfield, down to Avign
on, and down to the South of France. I had just hitchhiked from the south of France, back to London, and then from London to Skye, to meet my brother there, who was climbing in the Cuillins. And we went on climbing, we went on walking around together, unt
il we heard War broke out, then we dashed back to St Albans, by hitchhiking, of course, and joined the Aircraft Observation Post I think it was. Anyhow, I went back to Cambridge when term began.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Was that the ARP 
\endash  the Air Raid Protection \endash  ARP?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I think that\rquote 
s what it would be. I think that\rquote s what it must have been. And I can remember going down, being in a dugout, and looking out for things. But we came up to Cambridge when term began, with my brother, but by that time it was obvious I wasn\rquote t g
oing to have long around there because I was reading arts. If you were reading a science you got kept on in your degree, arts you went away. So I hastily joined, because I never was in it before, the Cambridge University Training Corps, and so I then went
 
before some Board here to sign me to go to Sandhurst. And I went to Sandhurst with my friend Matthew Hodgart, who later became Professor of English in Sussex, and was another of the stalwarts of the Socialist Party at that time, and we went down to Camber
ley. And we met somebody called Chris [Dominic] Rieu, whose father ran that Penguin series of England Classics, and he too had been a member of the Communist Party. So we started a small group in Sandhurst \endash 
 not exactly a Communist Group, because by then we\rquote d become rather dissatisfied with the British Communist Party\rquote 
s line on the War. However, it was through that we met. And we became soldiers in Sandhurst, just like Prince William! And my friend, Matthew Hodgart, was a first class intellectual, and he had read things like Clausewitz long before anybody else \endash 
 well, of my generation. So he immediately moved into Intelligence, and got promoted high up. I wanted to go into an infantry regiment ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab One thing I\rquote 
m not clear, you actually volunteered, then, did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh yes, because one knew war was coming. Well, war had already come, and people were being called up by ages, and I was a volunteer a month or two before I would have been called up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab And t
hen you went straight from volunteering to Sandhurst, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, I went straight from here to Sandhurst.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And is that because you were a Cambridge undergraduate that you were presumed to be [officer material]?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, at school I\rquote 
d been in an Officer Training Corps, and had got quite high up in it, so it was partly that and partly Cambridge, and also partly because when war broke out, we had to volunteer for something. We were very much imbued with Spain and the anti-Fascist strug
gle, and these manoeuvres of the Soviet Union and so on were not much to our liking at the time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
But had you earlier actually joined the Communist Party?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh yes. Six months before, I suppose. Well, I don\rquote t know, six, four, something like that, around four to six.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And when did you leave it?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15365386 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, not deliberately. I mean, I just didn\rquote t know anything about it! I didn\rquote 
t keep up with it, and some were much more against the Soviet Union and its war on Finland, of course, but I was certainly against the Ribbentrop Pact, because so much of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4279266 one\rquote s side }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 had been devoted to stru}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9335126 ggling against that very thing.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
So I went to Sandhurst, and I was sent to join the Sherwood Foresters, a regiment set around Nottingham and Derby, and I was posted to
 their First Battalion, which was a regular battalion, which was stationed in the Middle East, in Haifa, at that time. So I was going to be sent out there to join them, but I went up to Liverpool to board a ship, but then all ships going to the Mediterran
e
an were cancelled because Italy came into the War at the time that France fell. So I found myself looking after French prisoners-of-war on the race course at Liverpool, and these were people who were not following de Gaulle, and it always impressed me how
 many people wanted to go back, wanted to go home at that time, in France, and di}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9335126 dn\rquote t want to carry on fighting.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I was sent down from Liverpool to the East Coast here. I can remember the train journey through King\rquote s Lynn very well, to somewhere called Over
strand, where I and a few men took over a part of the coast, with a machine gun dating from the First World War! What would have happened if anyone had invaded, I don\rquote t know! But, anyhow, we went there, and stayed there for some time \endash  I can
\rquote t remember how long \endash 
 until in the end we were sent back to Liverpool and went on a ship to go to Egypt. By this time, of course, the Mediterranean was closed, so we had to go right down to Sierra Leone, almost across the Atlantic, back to South Africa. We stopped }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9335126 a little while in South Africa.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
And then up to Egypt, and then on to Cyprus. Because the Regiment I had been in, which had been struggling in Palestine against both Jews and Arabs \endash  they were equally, for us, they were terrorists, both of them. Well, particula
rly the Jewish because they had just blown up the George V Hotel, in Jerusalem, and killed somebody in Cairo. But my Regiment had gone to defend Cyprus, and there wasn\rquote 
t anyone there except the Regiment I was in, was in Cyprus. Very interesting actually, because before the War, the Regiment I was in, of 700 men, had one battalion in the Sudan, one battalion in Haifa, and one in Cyprus \endash  that was the level of}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15365386  supervision \'85 (?? \endash  12.49) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
was of the Colonial Empire at that time \endash  700 men for all those three territories. It\rquote s incredible when one thinks what\rquote 
s happened since, and now. It was very low level. When I was going out to Cyprus, I remember getting a list of instructions of what I was to take out, which was a lounge suit, tennis racquet, and Heaven knows 
what! I forget now! But those were on the list. So I went out with a lounge suit, I never wore it. Anyhow, I went to Cyprus and trained there with the First Battalion of Sherwood Foresters. I got to know some of the young officers who were my age, and als
o
 amateurs, like me, quite well, including somebody that I eventually escaped with, called Frank Fisher, who was the son of the [future] Archbishop of Canterbury [Geoffrey Fisher], and a man called Smith-Dorrien, who was the son of a General in the First W
orld War, called Smith-Dorrien. We all escaped later on. We escaped, went to Italy. So we were in Cyprus, and we did the usual things there \endash  t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15365386 
raining and drinking and so on.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Then we were transferred to Egypt, and where we\rquote d been one battalion in Cyprus, t
he whole Division took over from us, and we went to Egypt to fight and move up to the desert. We went to the pyramids. We were camped near the Giza Pyramids, in camp, and I can remember going to the Great Pyramid in the morning, and getting my platoon to 
clamber up, as part of the morning exercise, and I don\rquote t remember doing it myself! But ... and then we went off to the desert. And after a short while I was captured in Tobruk, and flown over.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
When did you say you were captured?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab In Tobruk? I s
uppose it was in June of 1942.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Did the experience of fighting make a big impression on you, or not?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid69802 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Not really, because in the desert you weren\rquote t really fighting like you were in the First World War. It\rquote s much more [as] if you
\rquote re at sea, that is to say that people got round the back of you in armoured cars, and you had to escape, or you got round the back of somebody else, it was much more mobile in that sense. I won\rquote t say I wasn\rquote t shot at, and I didn
\rquote t raise my rifle, but my gun I did, but not much. Very little. It wasn\rquote t fighting in that kind of sense, and not the sort of thing that happened at Monte Cassino or something like that. Very much manoeuvring around. So, no, it didn\rquote 
t make much impression. I mean, the bombarding bit \endash 
 being bombarded by these German Stukas that seemed as if they were coming down at you, like that, and you had nowhere to go, except hide in some trench. The bombardments, aerial bombardments, did make an impression, and I can\rquote 
t say I enjoyed that at all. But otherwise, if you think of those films about the desert, those war}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13372605 \'85 (?? - 18.31) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 and that sort of thing, you weren\rquote t really fighting close, except for a few minutes, at any time, and we were fighting close only really when the Germans broke through th
e wire, broke through the wire at Tobruk, which we never thought they would do, because the New Zealanders and Australians had been there before, for six months, and held out, and we were there for a few days and they broke through. So we were put into ca
mp, and then eventually taken to Benghazi, and flown back to Italy.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid69802   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 And then we were flown across to Italy in aeroplanes that had been bringing supplies over to North Africa, and we went to Italy, and were put in prison camp \endash 
 in Bari, for a short time. And then we went by train, further up, to near Pescara, which is about the same latitude as Rome, but on the Adriatic side. The camp was a little inland from that, at a place called Chieti \endash 
 which now has a University of Chieti \endash  and we were in a prison camp there. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So can you give a description of what this camp was like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, it was a large courtyard area with various brick-built huts on it. I\rquote d say there were about ten of them \endash  five on each side \endash 
 and an open area in the middle, and a wall around it. I went back there not long ago, with Juliet, well, she met us nearby, it\rquote s now become a training camp for Carabinieri \endash  for policemen \endash 
 but at that time, it was a PoW Camp, and it held all the junior officers captured in the desert, it held them there. And we had Italian guards in tall pill-boxes situated around the camp.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And what sort of regime was there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, the regime was not particularly harsh, in that sense. We just had roll call every day. You see, as officers, under the Geneva Convention \endash  which the Italians observed, even if the Americans don\rquote t \endash 
 officers did not work. They got less food than other ranks \endash  soldiers who could work outside \endash  but they were not made to work. So we had
 nothing to do. But we were all young officers about my age, many of us had been at university or something like that, and we started up, soon after we got there, we started up a vigorous educational programme, really it was very extensive \endash 
 for everything, including the priesthood \endash  and I can remember teaching something about English literature, but also taking a course in psychology and Italian and other things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Were you teaching or learning?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I was teaching modern poetry.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab And I think 
you said that there was a theatre in the camp?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15689471 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15689471 rigorous }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
theatre, in which my friend, David Smith-Dorrien, one of these young officers in the Regiment, I told you about, who had been in the theatre before, and was again afterwards, he was v
ery vigorous in that. And we had an interesting theatrical programme. The big dining room was turned into a theatre, and every month we had one classical play; we had one West End production that we remembered \endash 
 we had to remember these; we had one play that somebody wrote in the camp; and we had one musical, something like this; and every Saturday we had a kind of Music Hall, which went into three sessions. And on Sunday, we used to have music. We didn\rquote 
t have many scores, but we could get, through the Red 
Cross, we got a gramophone, and we had somebody who became a music master at Marlborough I think, anyhow, he was a member of the British Academy later on [Anthony Baines?], and he used to sit down with his gramophone, and score \endash  write out \endash 
 what he heard, for the instruments that we had, which were few and far between. And he used to give a symphony concert every Sunday afternoon. And we had a booking office in the camp, run by somebody called Tennant, who, I\rquote 
m sure, was related to the booking people in Lo
ndon, in which you would get your ticket for a certain performance. It was very well-organised in that sense. So you knew you were going on Tuesday night to see this play, with certain people in, and you knew you were going to the Music Hall at six o
\rquote clock, or eight o\rquote clock or something, on Saturday,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15689471  and it was all very organised.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The teaching, too, was highly organised. A timetable. And what we didn\rquote t have much of was reading material, and we had no library, and the Italians were not very keen on letting 
us have Italian books, neither were the Germans in Germany \endash  I don\rquote t know why. But in Germany, we had a very good library \endash 
 that was later on. In Italy we had no books at all, virtually, until the very end of the time, when we started getting some book parcels from England.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
