Were you impressed by the way that all this cultural activity was created out of nothing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Very. Very impressed. Well, when you see a lot of soldiers walking down the street, you don\rquote t immediately think of someone amongst them teaching Freud or Pavlov, or whatever! But yes, it was extraordinary, really, how this grew up suddenly \endash 
 both on the artistic side and on the intellectual side. It was very interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab And then there
\rquote s another thing you said, that the diversity of people you mixed with in this phase aroused your curiosity. Could you explain about that?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid1405229 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I don\rquote t know if I can say much more, but you were thrown up against people in very close contact, and in 
the group that I was in, they came from my Regiment, and we\rquote d all been taken prisoners together. There was Frank Fisher who was up here at the same time as I was, but he was from Repton where his father \endash  the Archbishop \endash 
 had been Headmaster. There was an historian who was working in the theatre, but came from a military family. And the fourth member was Edward, who was a butcher in South London, but had been promoted through the ranks thereafter, so you were with a l}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1405229 ot of different people.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 When I escaped,
 I escaped for six months, even more so. I was in a cave with them, first of all, and later on with some South Africans and two guys who, I think, were Nottinghamshire miners. But anyhow, people who were in a completely different way of life. Because all 
the things that I\rquote ve been describing to you \endash  school, university \endash  you were simply somebody concerned with books and books and books, you weren\rquote 
t concerned with doing things like cutting up meat or even acting on the stage, so it was very different in that 
way. So I think you met a lot of people with a lot of different experiences, and particularly, as I say, many of the people in my regiment I met then and afterwards, were Nottinghamshire miners, who had joined the Regular Army because they were out of a j
ob, and this was the sort of person that you were meeting.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
But you were also coming across very different cultures, weren\rquote t you, when you were fighting as well as in the camp?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I was. I was trying to think. Of course, if you were in a military camp, it didn\rquote t matter whether you were in Iraq or Afghanistan, you didn\rquote 
t learn much about what happened around you. But you did in Cyprus, because at certain times I went into the villages, no doubt for military inspections or something, but you certainly did then, but it was more particularly after I\rquote 
d been in Italy, at the end of the Armistice there when I escaped for six months, then I was with villagers, and I learned much more about culture then. I learnt a certain amount, obviously, in the Near East
, I mean, climbing up these pyramids and so on, but not very much on a sort of personal way until I got to Italy, and lived very close and had to live in houses, in villagers\rquote  houses, to get food and to get a night\rquote s rest.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So how long was it before you escaped?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
