\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab But going to Eichst
\'e4tt, I think was very important, wasn\rquote t it, for the books you found in the library there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Eichst\'e4
tt was quite different, yes, and had this excellent library. When I got to Eichst\'e4tt, there were people the
re who had been there since Dunkirk. They received a lot of books all the time, because you were allowed to send a parcel of books every month or two \endash  I forget what it was \endash  but anyhow, we had a very good collection of books in Eichst\'e4
tt, so I was able, there, to read. Well, the two books I remember were [E. K.] Chambers\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Mediaeval Stage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  and [James Frazer\rquote s] }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The Golden Bough}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , which, of course, were mentioned in T.S. Eliot\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Waste Land}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , which is why I started reading it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And you were impressed by it, were you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Very interested by it, yes, but perhaps in 
relationship to English more than my relationship to English literature, more than anything else. I mean, it was mentioned by Eliot in the same breath as Jessie Weston on mediaeval romance. And so it was a sort of background to release.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab There was an
other book you mentioned, Gordon Childe, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 What Happened in History}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. I was very impressed with Gordon Childe, because he made sense to me of something I\rquote d never really thought about, and that was the Middle East, where I went. And I remember, whe
n I was in Cyprus, going round a museum there and seeing a clay model of a bullock, from the third millennium BC, of a bullock pulling a plough, and it was precisely the same sort of Mediterranean plough that Marc Bloch talks about, or that you saw even t
o
day, going around, scratching the surface of the land, and the continuity of that, and the fact that that was still being used, yes, impressed me very much. So I was very impressed all the time, and have been ever since, with the achievements of the Bronz
e Age and which writing was what, and how they affected modern society. And, of course, Childe also \endash  he wasn\rquote t only in Cyprus and Palestine \endash  but also Egypt, where I was wandering around pyramids, as I mentioned \endash 
 not in a very scholarly way \endash  but Childe made sense of these things very much. So I was very impressed with Childe. Very impressed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And would it be true that these books were crucial in your decision to become an anthropologist?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, I suppose so. There were various things, of cours
e, but obviously the reading was one thing. Another thing would have been the theatre. Quite apart from the books, you came in contact with other cultures in a different way, and particularly in Italy where I got very close to people, but also in Cyprus a
s well, to some extent. But it was not only that, I was also interested in the wider problem of human conflict. Indeed, one of the things I subscribed to not long ago, I mean some time ago, was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The Journal of Conflict Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , and I suppose that\rquote s why I was
 interested. And also in the Tavi. The Tavi\rquote s interest, to me, was the avoidance of human conflict.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So how did you come into contact with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well (a) because they had a special dispensational grant or whatever, from the government, for looking after prisoners-of-war, so when I came back afterwards, there was an invitation to go to the Tavi if I wanted to. I didn\rquote 
t, in fact, go. There was an article which I read, by Edward Shils, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Pilot Papers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\delrsid4728311\charrsid677667  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 about American sociology, which talked about t
he rapprochement with psychology and with psychoanalysis, and mentioned the Tavi, and the letter I had from Edward Shils, I think that\rquote s how I came in contact with them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And anthropology, was that just an idea \endash  because you\rquote ve mentioned Frazer, but there\rquote s no other person you\rquote ve mentioned.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Not really. That was just an idea. I mean, it wasn\rquote t till I came back here and started reading anthropology that I knew about Evans-Pritchard, for example. I mean, I read anthropology here [but] if they\rquote d ha
ve had sociology at the time, I would not have read anthropology, partly because, at that time, anthropologists were not interested in European studies \endash  at least Evans-Pritchard and company certainly were not. So it wasn\rquote 
t until people like my friend Julian Pitt-Rivers started on Spain, and other people on Mediterranean studies. But they weren\rquote 
t really interested. [W. M.] Williams is the same, but he was a sociologist. That was meant to be quite different from anthropology in some ways. So they were not in
terested in that. Even later on, as an anthropologist, when I went to Oxford, and I wanted to work on Italian village life, I was told that first of all you had to learn about some other society, so that\rquote s why I went to Africa \endash 
 never got back!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab So w
ho were your teachers at Cambridge?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab We didn\rquote 
t really have any teachers in anthropology here. Evans-Pritchard came over once a week, as I say, to give his lecture, and then go. There was nobody else virtually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So Meyer Fortes comes in later?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Later on. I came back to Meyer Fortes. He was not here then. And Leach came back. Then there was a curious Swede, American Swede, who worked among the Lapps [Sami] \endash  they were non-European \endash 
 and Reo Fortune, who had been a distinguished anthropologist, but by the time I knew him, had cracked up. And that was about all. I was taught by somebody here, in this College, who taught myself and Godfrey Lienhardt, he was an archaeologist \endash 
 Glyn Daniel. He taught me at that time. And he taught Godfrey. And God
frey was another Leavis pupil, who had had an article published before he ever took up anthropology. And then he went to Oxford straightaway after, to work with Evans-Pritchard, whereas I went into education. I went into further education, yes.
\par 
\par [CHANGE OF TAPE]
