 interested in historical work. Partly because the Nuer had no written history, but I never thought they looked upon it much in that way, they looked upon it, not as I did, as a matter of the historical dimension of technique as the influence, but in term
s of something more spiritual, more nebulous. I always think one of L\'e9vi-Strauss\rquote s distinctions between the bricolage of the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6231102  Neolithic \endash 
 what he calls the \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 primitive }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
pens\'e9e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6231102 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
 and other thinking. He never, once, thinks in terms of the mechanisms that transfer
 from one to the other with literacy, for example, how it made a difference. And EP [Evans-Pritchard], I think, was something of the same. He was a historian by training, and he did a certain amount of history on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af0\afs22 
