\rquote s in Oxford.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So, just looking at the scene in Oxford and Cambridge, would it be fair to say that, in Oxford, EP did create a kind of school ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Absolutely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
... with his own group, and at Cambridge that wasn\rquote t happening when you were here?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Not at all. Far from it. I
\rquote m not sure that EP created it. It may have been Radcliffe-Brown, who was the first professor, who created it, but EP was certainly much more vigorous than Radcliffe-Brown was, and undoubtedly [it was] he who recruited Meyer Forte
s and Max Gluckman and others. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And was that when you started working with Meyer Fortes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. I went there. I had a family by that time \endash  a wife, at least one child, if not two \endash  and I was determined I had to get over this hump of looking at some other culture, but I didn\rquote 
t want to go out to New Guinea or anywhere like that, it seemed too far, so I opted for somewhere \endash  well, it wasn\rquote t entirely true to say that, it was fortunate because I met a Ghanaian here, and got interested in Ghana.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Who was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
A chap who became the Attorney-General of Ghana at one time. He was the son of a historian, called Joe Reindorf, and his father, I think his father, perhaps, had been one of the first historians of Ghana. Reindorf [was] a Danish name from Accra. And I
\rquote d shared a room with Joe, at a house near here, in Nine Elms Road}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6846444  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , and so when I wanted to go abroad I had an inclination to go there. And also I could go there and come back [more easily].
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
You said the name is Danish. So was he mixed-race?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, had been a long time ago. He was African now. You see, Accra was a Danish fort at one time, and he was completely African, but his name was Danish. The grandfather, I think it was, had done this history of Ghana. But he read la
w here, he read history first, and then law, and became eventually, at one stage, became Attorney-General in Ghana. And so I went out to Ghana. I decided to go to Ghana partly because I could come back by mail boat, at that time. I mean, it wasn\rquote 
t like nowadays where you can fly out anywhere in 24 hours, or six hours I think it is to Ghana. You took 12 days by steam ship. But I went out, and I went out third class \endash  steerage, as they call it \endash 
 so that I could come back in the middle to see my family, so I didn\rquote t have to be away for two years in one go. So I chose Ghana in that sense, that double sense, it was most convenient to get back, that way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Isn\rquote 
t it also related to Meyer Fortes\rquote  interests?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, I think I chose Meyer Fortes because I wanted to go somewhere nearer. I think that was the answer.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
What was he like as a supervisor, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Very pleasant, I thought. He was very helpful. I don\rquote t say that he went through each of my manuscripts in quite the way I might have done to later students, but he was perhaps more aloof. But he was very friendly, very helpful to me. But I don
\rquote t think I wanted to be bothered very much with a supervisor who was on my back the whole time, and I don\rquote t think I needed much [help] in order to write my thesis. Writing came comparatively easy to me, I suppose, perhaps because I\rquote 
d done English before.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
But his ideas on kinship, for instance, they were perhaps the starting point for your description?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh, certainly. Certainly. I mean, I don\rquote 
t think I had any ideas on kinship before. I mean, I had ideas on literacy before, because they came from a different source, but kinship was very much Evans-Pritchard and Fortes, and kinship was, after all, the talk of the town at that time. Even my frie
nds like Peter Worsley and Kathleen Gough, and Cliff Slaughter \endash  did you ever know Cliff Slaughter, who wrote, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Coal is our Life}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh, I know the book, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
[He] read anthropology here. Even he was interested in kinship. Everyone was at that time. It was the intellectual thing. I ask myself why [it was], sometimes, that other aspects weren\rquote t more taken up. Well, I won\rquote t say they weren\rquote 
t taken up. Obviously people did take up topics like religion and politics, but never quite in the same systematic way.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I was wondering whether you could describe the practical side of going to Ghana and setting yourself up in the field?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid14318726 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I went out on this boat, Dempster Lines. I went out steerage. There was somebody very nice in the Colonial Offi
ce Research Department, called Sally Chilver, who became Head of an Oxford College I think, who was a historian, incidentally, who allowed me to split my travel money to go out twice. But I went on the boat train up to Liverpool, and I was met there by so
mebody from the Dempster Line, who said to me, \'93You do realise you\rquote re travelling with a lot of black gentlemen?\'94 I said, \'93Well, I suppose I\rquote ll have to get used to that, because I\rquote m going out to study them\'94
. So I was allowed to get on, and I got on this boat \endash  it was rather depressing, right down in the hold \endash 
 and we were allowed up on deck for what, half an hour or an hour every day. But I had very interesting company down there because the Africans I was with, you know, one was a lawyer, one was a doctor. I can\rquote 
t remember the others very much, but they\rquote re the people who were in my cabin, so I probably had a lot more intelligent conversation down there than I did up in second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14568394  or first class with Europeans.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Anyhow, I was met in Ghana by a former student of Me
yer Fortes, or a friend of his, I can\rquote t remember now, when I met Kofi. The former student\rquote 
s name was Kofi Busia, who wrote a book on the Ashanti, and eventually became Prime Minister after Nkrumah. He was Head of the Sociology Department in Legon, and he l
ooked after me. I suppose, through having been a prisoner-of-war, and also I felt my age was against me, I wanted to get things done as quickly as I could, so time was very important to me, so I didn\rquote 
t spend long in Accra at that time, in the capital. I got my permits or whatever I had to do, got my kit together, and my food, made my arrangements very quickly, always did. And I always felt that time\rquote 
s winged chariot was hurrying near, even at that time, and I was doing what a lot of people had done}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14318726  much earlier, so I hurried up.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I went up to Kumasi, which was the capital of the Division of Ashanti, and I met somebody who knew Meyer Fortes quite well there, an administrator in education, calle
d Peter Cannon, and he fixed me up to go further on in a government lorry. I was a Colonial Officer at that time. Because my Scholarship was a Colonial Office one, so I was going out there as a Colonial Officer. And he also found me a cook/steward from th
e area I was g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14318726 oing to, which was most useful.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
So I went there with him, up to the North, and I stopped the night when I got into the Northern Territories, in a huge government rest house, built of mud, with sticks for a roof, but a vast place, where there was a man \endash 
 that I remember to this day \endash  the District Commissioner met me there, a very pleasant chap, and when we got there, said, \'93Well, we\rquote ll have to go out and shoot something for dinner tonight\'94
. So we went out and shot a guinea fowl, a wild one, and
 came back and cooked that. And then I went on the next day to the next government place, to see the District Commissioner there and his sister was married to an archaeologist in Cambridge, and he had a huge HMV gramophone \endash 
 like one of these ones you see in these ads \endash 
 which he turned up and played music on that, he was very proud of that! So I stayed there, and then went on, the next day, to the place where I was going to work. But even there, I stayed for a time in a rest house, a government rest house, 
before I went out to the village. But these rest houses, as I say, were built towards the beginning of the century, out of mud and grass on the roof, and they were fine for staying in \endash  a bit dusty, but that\rquote 
s what I was in. And there I got to know someone who was Headmaster of the local school, from the area, a very intelligent man who later, under Independence, himself became a District Commissioner, but told me a great deal about the area that I was in.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
