re, who was upper and who was lower to you [varied], so in a sense I found it very difficult to see where I was, to find out where I was, since it depended on what you were talking about. If you were talking about a certain sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6181342  of xylophone, people would be \lquote Lobi\rquote . In other ways they might be \lquote Dagarti\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 . So I had a lot of puzzling to do about how to work this out. Anyhow, in the end I worked out that I just wanted to go somewhere where I could work things }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6181342 out when I got there.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 As you ask on the p
ractical way of kit, well, in the short time I had in the South, I got together what I wanted, and wrapped them up, and had them in the back of the lorry that I\rquote 
d got for a short time from the government, and took it up with me. But, really, all I needed was a bed, and some sort of bath, and a lamp \endash  a pressure lamp \endash  plus food, plus beer.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So you took your own bed with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Bed? Yes. Yes, a camp bed. I think there was one in some of these rest houses.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab But in the village, 
did you have your own house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
In the village I went to, there was another rest house, which was not used by District Commissioners, because it was only 15 miles away from their Headquarters. There was something there which the local people had built,
 because they wanted one of the administrators to come out at certain times. They had built it, and it wasn\rquote t being used, so I went into that. But later on I went into a local house, which was vacant for other reasons.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Can you describe that house that you went into? The second one. I\rquote ve seen some plans of houses that you\rquote ve done.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
The second one, yes. They had thick mud walls, flat roofs \endash  unlike the rest house which had these flat roofs \endash  and no windows, in fact, that I can think of. I probabl
y ate on the roof upstairs, I think. But also, at that second place, it seemed to be very enclosed, this mud hut, and I remember that I had a tent that I borrowed, with me \endash  from the government supplies as well \endash 
 and I put the tent next to one side of the hut, and I opened up the hut a bit. I took some bricks out and made an entrance, and so I could go under the tent and leave the keys ... (?? \endash  38.27) there, and use that as a sort of office, which I did.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Did you cook for yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab No, no. Nev
er. Almost never.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So you had a servant for some things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I had this cook/steward.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Was that a man or a woman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Man. Always had this cook/steward with me, and wouldn\rquote t have done without it, because if you really had to go, as I woul
d have done, as he had to, to the river to get water, which was some way away, to the woods to chop down some wood, before you could light a fire and before you could do cooking, or before you could have made a bath, I would have spent the whole of my tim
e doing that. There was nothing like turning on a tap in any way, or lighting a gas oven! They had a lot of work to do. There were a few Quakers who came out, who had the idea that they could get on without employing domestic service}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6181342  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , but unless you\rquote re going to make your wife \endash 
 which I hadn\rquote t got out with me \endash  if you make your wife fetch water and fetch firewood, that\rquote s all right. But people don\rquote 
t realise what the difference is between that and a place here, where you simply switch on a switch and the light comes on, or the water or the cooker. I mean, all these things are a lot of work, and no, I wouldn\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309  have done anything if I\rquote d ... t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
o get food, I had to go to a market, I had to cycle some five miles or ten miles to a market to get some food, to get the food for the day.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So you did do that? Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
No. I went sometimes to the market, but not primarily for that. I think my cook/steward would have been very annoyed if I\rquote d have gone to the market, as he had his own arrangements to get me what he thought I should have. But, no, so I didn\rquote 
t do any of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And what, in terms of the methods? Participant observation? What did that involve? What were you observing?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8399309 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
What was I doing? Well, when I got there, I was in this hut on the top of the hill, and I just went down and started sniffing around one of these compounds, and somebody came out and was interested in who I was, and I tried to explain I was interested in
 learning the language \endash  I\rquote m not sure how this happened \endash  because soon afterwards I had to get somebody from the locality who would come round with me.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Even when I\rquote 
d learnt the language I needed somebody who I could check with, because you couldn\rquote t write 
down every word. Somebody I could check with when I got back. And so usually I used to go around with this chap, but I could go down by myself, and did go down by myself, and quite often I used to sit there drinking beer by myself, and I could soon unders
tand enough of the language. But I couldn\rquote t learn the language beforehand; I had to learn the language there, on the spot. Ordinary things I learnt fairly quickly, but obviously the meaning of religious concepts took some time, and, indeed, I don
\rquote t know that I understand them altogether now, because they\rquote re so variable. But that was very different.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I went to funerals a great deal, and partly because at funerals, a lot of people gathered there, funerals summed up a person\rquote s life in a biographical way \endash  what he\rquote 
d done during his time on earth and this sort of thing \endash 
 and also people had time to discuss things with you, so that you could sit there talking about inheritance in a relatively natural way, about this and that, and about quarrels that people had had,
 and so on, in a natural way, so that was very useful for me, to go to those. Also they lasted three days and three nights.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Really? Amazing!

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So that took a long time. The first day, second day, a third day, so you had a lot of time to discuss things. So, yes, I was a very assiduous attender of funerals. In fact, I began to wonder, at one time, whether people didn\rquote 
t think I brought them on so I could talk about these things! I got rather worried about it. But, no, I don\rquote t think they did! No, they were very pleased for me to go to a funeral.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Were you able to visit people and maybe eat with them in their houses?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So they were quite welcoming to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh yes. Certainly [I] would drink with them in their houses. The great thing was, in that area, that every day there was a certain house that brewed beer, which meant you could go there and buy it, and other people would be seen round drinking beer, so it
\rquote s like going to a pub. So [you\rquote d] sit around with the other people, and the conversation would be completely natural, you know. You could direct it, or they\rquote d direct it. So that was very easy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
What about observing women\rquote s roles, how would you do that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, the women had a role, of cou
rse, even in drinking. That is to say they were the brewers of beer, and they would serve it and sell it to you. There was also nothing to stop women sitting around drinking beer with you. In fact, that was quite common, and if you were well in with the w
oman, or she was in with you, you would drink out of a calabash, you would drink together \endash  she would drink on one side, you on the other side. But looking at the other aspects of women\rquote s work and women\rquote 
s activities, you certainly didn\rquote t interact with them 
in the same way as you did with men, except there was nothing much to stop you. It was not a Muslim area, and nothing to stop you walking into the kitchen, and sitting down there and looking at things, or going to the harvest or planting ground where wome
n were working in the field, there was nothing to stop you doing that, or perhaps in the market place. But inevitably there\rquote d be a slightly moral problem.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab A moral problem?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, [more] than with men. But on the other hand, you got a lot of leeway because you were a foreigner, so that you could do things that a local man could not do in that way. I mean, he probably couldn\rquote 
t walk into the kitchen, whereas you could. You had more leeway, I think, had more leeway as a stranger, because you weren\rquote t expected to know things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
How close to a woman could you get? If a woman, for instance, became an anthropologist\rquote s lover, would that be a dangerous situation, do you think?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid8399309 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab It was always said to be. It was always said to make difficulties. I mean, you\rquote 
re in a relatively small village, and villages in Africa are relatively small, compared with a village in India, a village in India is huge, often. Everybody knows everybody el
se in an African village, so they know directly if somebody visits you, or you visit somebody. There isn\rquote t any privacy in that sense. I mean, to lead a private life, you\rquote re in danger of being accused of witchcraft.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I always used to hide myself, not hide m
yself, but not be out in the open if I was writing field notes, which I did for a large part of the day, of course. I used to reckon I had to fill up ten pages a day, of field notes. But I didn\rquote 
t like to do that in public anyway, because I thought they would think this private activity was rather like witchcraft. So if you\rquote re down in the village, and somebody\rquote 
s sitting there, brooding away, you would wonder what they were up to, unless they were interacting with people. If they were interacting with people 
that was all right. I mean, I can well imagine why people in an English village thought those women who kept themselves to themselves were up to no good. And the way you get round that is by communicating with people. So I did a lot of communicating. But 
for some time I was rather dependent on my having somebody with me. I mean, you can learn, very quickly, to do a demographic enquiry, or a kinship enquiry about \'93who lives in this household?\'94 There\rquote 
s no problem about that. But directly somebody gets on to s
peaking about something more complicated, you know, like witchcraft, or like some concept, it becomes more difficult. I needed somebody that I could discuss that with afterwards, and say, you know, \'93How would you look at this idea?\'94
 So there were some things, like a demographic survey, you could do perfectly well, and which I would do on my own, but when somebody started to speak to me about other things, then often you needed somebody with you, that you could talk to in that way.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par [CHANGE OF TAPE]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I
 was hoping we could go on talking a little bit longer about fieldwork, and one of the things which I was interested by was ... of course you published the book called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The Myth of the Bagre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes. Several books.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Indeed, yes. And I think you\rquote ve even said that it was the thing you were most proud of. Is that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, I think so. A translation. I mean, I took such a lot of time and work in doing that. I used to drive down from London every week, to London from here, every weekend, to work with my friend down there, when he had an accident.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Which friend was this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
The one I edited the biography of, called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 A Silent Rebel}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , which is up there. He was called Kumbano}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8399309 Gandah, from the village, \lquote Kum\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 . But he came over here to wor
k here, and I used to go and work with him every weekend, really, in North-West London. I was very pleased to have done it, partly because it threw such a different light on things for me, particularly the learning process, because I had thought that this
 myth was fairly standardised \endash  that\rquote s what I was told \endash  but I really didn\rquote t }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14756217 understand, at that time, what \lquote sameness\rquote }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  meant, if you didn\rquote t have a written copy. So it was a great surprise to me, and an even greater surprise to my co-worker, when these versi
ons turned out to be so different from one another. So that led me to query, very much \endash  I should have known that from my work on oral societies, but I didn\rquote 
t really appreciate, and it made me query, very much, the kind of analysis on myth that my friend Claude L\'e9vi-Strauss did. Because I then realised there wasn\rquote t simply one version that was linked with society, there were several \endash 
 I mean, an infinite number \endash  and that people\rquote s creative abilities had been much underplayed. Until we had a tape recorder like this, of course, we couldn\rquote t really tell. The great effort of writing down one version, you\rquote 
d raise your hands and say, \'93Not another!\'94 But when you\rquote ve got one of these [recorders], you realise that each recording is different. And it adds up to being significantly different.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
The first time you recorded was without a machine.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, was when I had no recording machine. I did [it] by hand. Well, they didn\rquote t exist at that time, the transistor had not been invented, or adapted. And the first time 
I did recordings was some years later, in Gonja, in a different area, where I got flown a machine from the BBC. It was an old German machine, which was used to play things in the trenches, or record things in the trenches \endash 
 it worked on a battery, and had valves \endash 
 that was flown out to me, and I took it, with great difficulty, to an African village, and actually used to broadcast. I did a broadcast of it when it returned. But that was so heavy that you needed somebody to carry it around if you haven\rquote t got a
 car. It was only later on that the portable tape recorder turned up, and I then went with my friend, Kumbano, back to the first place I\rquote d been to, and made some recordings at that time, and we\rquote ve recorded ever since.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Oh, really? You
\rquote re still recording?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, not today, no. I mean, until he died a couple of year[s] ago, three years ago, he and I went out to record things. Not only that, but at one time we sent a recording machine to one of his relatives to make a recording, it wasn\rquote 
t necessary for us to be there, except it wasn\rquote t very successful, but it could be done. And the locals, too, were using recording machines to record prayers and other things. But I won\rquote 
t say the short prayers, even the short prayers that I recorded, differed somewhat, each version verbally, but on the longer recitations, they differed enormously over a few years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
But what was the role of Benima Dagarti?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Benima, he was the first one. He was the person who first came out with me and said that he knew this myth, and he recited me it \endash  the first version \endash 
 and I had a pencil and paper, carbon paper, and I wrote out everything as he recited it. But after that I used a recorder. The recorded versions, incidentally, for whatever reason, are always shorter than the ones that I\rquote 
ve written by hand. I think he probably explained more as he was going along, and writing out like that. Also he had to wait for me to finish my script at the time. But that took me something like ten days to record, so I wouldn\rquote 
t have done that again unless I had a tape recorder, and I wouldn\rquote t have known the versions differed over time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Was the myth a secret, or in the open?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
It was secret. It was only available to initiates in the society. And even when I took my
 tape recorder there subsequently, I had to leave the tape recorder with my friend in one room, and I had to go to another. I went to another. So it was certainly secret in that sense, it was limited in that sense, to those members who had been through th
e initiation procedures \endash  which I never went through fully.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
You did start, then, did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, I did some of the sacrifices, but it meant sitting, in theory, naked, for a week \endash  or was it two weeks? And that didn\rquote t seem, to me, the best way of using my grant! In silence, I should say. That didn\rquote 
t seem, to me, the best way of doing it, and I wasn\rquote t quite sure what extra I would learn.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, you\rquote 
d become one of the group, wouldn\rquote t you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, I would. But becoming one of the group probably means you can\rquote t ... I remember one anthropologist, I think it was Kenneth Little, who worked in Sierra Leone, who came back, he said he couldn\rquote 
t say anything about this because he was a member of the group, and pledged to secrecy. That also seemed, to me, less than profitable.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So you drew the line there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And on this kind of point, I\rquote m interested that you did become politically active.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well I wasn\rquote 
t very active. I did join a local CVP}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14756217  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
 [Convention People\rquote s Party] which was Nkrumah\rquote s Party. I did join that, yes, because I was in favour of Independence for these countries. But I didn\rquote t really do much else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I guess some people would say that anthropologists ought to stay neutral in the field. What\rquote s your feeling about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I didn\rquote 
t think it would make much difference. But anyhow, at the time, I thought it would be useful to attend these local meetings, and that was the only way I could do so. So I was interested in seeing what was goin
g on, and no doubt if the opposition party had also been there, canvassing the area, I might have joined that as well! But my sympathies were more with the CVP at that time. Yes, I think that if you\rquote 
re in a political situation, which was very divided, possibly, yes, you would be better to remain apart in any quarrel, but you hoped to take that with a pinch of salt in that, unless you get in a little to whatever the situation is \endash 
 domestic or national \endash  you aren\rquote t going to learn anything, and so you hope to 
get a certain way towards the conflict situation, I think, in order to be able to report on it at all. And you can only bring out the fact that you are related to one party, or you had something to do with one party rather than another, I suppose, but I t
hink that\rquote s constantly going to happen in that situation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
You could argue, perhaps, that it\rquote s important to show people you\rquote re on their side, in order to gain their confidence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I think that\rquote 
s true, except that if the situation is very divisive, to be on somebody\rquote s side means to be }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5656540 (??) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 you\rquote 
re against somebody else, and that does make it difficult, I think. That does make it difficult. But I think one just has to judge these situations as they come, and to be relatively open about which side you\rquote re on \endash 
 if there is a question of sides.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. Okay. And as I understand it, you went first to the LoWiili from August 1950, to September 1951.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And then there was a gap, and you came back in 1952, March to December, with the LoDagaba.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, that\rquote 
s right. They were two different sizes and groups, from the point of view of inheritance. Not very different, and in most respects they were very similar, but there were certain differences \endash  in that the first one is distinctly matrilineal}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5656540  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, whereas the second one was one that inherited moveable property down the maternal line, through the mother, and through the uncle and the sister\rquote s son, but otherwise, they were very similar. So I wanted to see what the differences
 were in these two. And I also went, partly, to the second group, who are more Christian, because that area they were in, it had been heavily influenced by Christianity, and I thought I might learn more about the Bagre in that area than I had done. It was
n\rquote t true, in fact. And as you say, I didn\rquote t learn that. I learnt other things, but I didn\rquote t learn that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So this was a change of plan, after you\rquote d done the first bit of fieldwork?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
As a result of the first fieldwork. It was a change of plan, yes. I\rquote 
d started the first fieldwork. I decided I wanted to know more about that side of things. You see, I thought the area that I was in, this matrilineal, or LoWiili one, was [now] very much against matrilineal inheritance of anything, but they were obviou
sly very conscious of it, and it seemed to me that, in the not too distant past, they had used it, they had employed that system. But now they didn\rquote 
t, and were very much against it. And I wanted to see more into this, and also how marriage worked under these systems, because if you marry somebody from one of these other areas, you get pulled into it, or the children would, and that\rquote 
s what I wanted to see. So that\rquote s why I moved away a bit, and worked in both. And also, in the first area, I had recorded the B
agre. I did work on the Bagre in the second area, because what I did, I got somebody out there to help me translate it. I had done a rough translation when I was with this chap you mentioned, with Benima, but I certainly did do a lot of work on translatio
n
, and partly, I thought, in this other area it would be easier. Well, it was, because they no longer practised it because of Christianity, so that part was easier, so I did get more translation done, more help with the translation. At the other place, it 
was very difficult for me to show anyone what I\rquote d done, or discuss it with them, because it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid11029768  was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  secret, whereas in the second area, it was not.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I noticed you thanked Gerard Charles and Guy Dyer Ball. Who were they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Gerard Charles was the person whose sister was married to an archaeologist here, somebody called [Charles] McBurney (?? \endash  sp.), and I gather her child, her son, is very well-known in the theatrical world in London \endash  Simon McBurney (?? 
\endash  20.35). And Dyer Ball \endash  they were both Commissioners \endash  and Dyer Ball had been at Oxford, and I guess he\rquote d been in the Army too, in the Army in Africa. He came from a vaguely Colonial past, because there was a Dyer Ball 
\endash  and I knew the name \endash  who wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The History of Hong Kong}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, or something about Hong Kong, which must have been a relative, close relative. So he was the local Commissioner, and his wife had also been in Oxford, so their house was a relief to go back to at times when I went over there. And he was very helpful to
 me with administrative papers and that sort of thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Apart from the two people involved in the Bagre and the man who became Attorney-General, were there other close friends you made in Ghana, that you kept up with later?
\par 
