Yes, because, you see, I did my second lot of fieldwork with young children, and my second wife, Esther, who is out there now, I did a lot of work, I went out there for another two years, to work among the Gonja, which E
sther wrote up for her Ph.D., but I did a lot of work there, largely historical work, which I have never done anything with. I was fairly closely attached to Legon, the Institute of African Studies, which was then directed by my friend Thomas Hodgkin, and
 the Head of the University then was the Irishman, [Conor Cruise] O\rquote 
Brien, from the Congo. So I knew both of them. And I knew a lot of people in the Sociology Department. I used to get invited back to mark papers. I went out sometimes for my own reasons \endash  to record the Bagre, or to do something \endash 
 so I kept on fairly regularly, yes.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid733225   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I can\rquote 
t remember, now, the last time I went back. Oh, I went back with Juliet a while ago, to go to a conference, but I didn\rquote t go up North. The last time I went up North I can\rquote t remember, but it was certainly probably with Kum, my friend Kum 
\endash  that was some years ago. I found it increasingly difficult. I was not attached to the government or anything, or the University, so I had to find my own way around, and finding your own way 
around Africa meant jumping on and off buses in the heat, or else climbing on lorries, and I found this very tiring to do, and not conducive to doing much work, whereas before, when I had the Colonial Scholarship, I got ferried around \endash 
 not often, but I did do, and that was much easier. It\rquote s not an easy place to get around now, unless you\rquote ve got a lot of money and can buy a car or hire one. If you\rquote re a journalist and can do that, you\rquote 
re okay, you can get round, but an ordinary person, it\rquote s not easy.
