\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid14092304 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Oh yes, I think so, very much. I mean, I wouldn\rquote t be able to specify exactly the changes, because I haven\rquote 
t been there recently, but when I was last there, there were a lot of people like my friend, Kum, who was here over here, working in Guinness (?? \endash 
 30.52) as a statistician, but he had done statistics through doing courses in history and philosophy of science at the same time as working with me on the Bagre.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid733225 
  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But at the same time, most of the village, an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid733225 
d the people he would call his \lquote uneducated brothers\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  would be doing hoe farming \endash  not ploughing with a cow, but hoe farming 
\endash  hard, back-breaking work, most of them, because I often pointed out the [plough] never reached Africa, it was never
 taken up in Africa. So that all farming was hoe farming until missionaries and others came in with horses and did a bit of ploughing in some places.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid733225   }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But most places in Ghana, of course, directly you start ploughing, you upset the whole system of land ten
ure at that time, because you need a lot more land for ploughing, or you can plough a lot more land than you can farm with a hoe. So immediately people started ploughing, they started claiming a lot of land, unploughed land, possibly, but they started cla
iming that. Yes, there was hoeing, but it led to a lot of stratification, and you got a lot more social distinction. [It was a] fairly egalitarian society, the sort of thing tha}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14092304 t EP would have referred to as \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 ordered an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14092304 archy\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, [but became] much more economic class-bound, and educational class, because there was such a difference between the literates and the non-literates, in terms of what jobs they could do. Which, of course, though we don\rquote 
t recognise it, was true in most of European history, as, say, those that didn\rquote t go to a Koranic School, or didn\rquote t go to a Cathedral School, were at an enormous disadvantage as far as so many jobs were concerned. And that\rquote 
s the same but only worse in Ghana now. You don\rquote t really get elected to go to a Parliament unless you can read and write, because Parliament works on all these papers, and it\rquote 
s got to be literate for it to work at all. So, as they say, in that sense, it\rquote s very unrepresentative. I think that is partly what I would find much more difficult now, much more different.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14092304   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
But the markets, the local markets and so on, seem to be much the same. And when I went back, not long ago, to this conference, I did go round a bit locally, mostly in Accra and around the capital, because of my fri
end Christine Oppong, but the local markets didn\rquote 
t seem much different. On the other hand, so many people have been going to university, or going to secondary school and things like that, that this certainly has made a difference. So everybody had uneducat
ed brothers as well as educated ones, and that made quite a lot of difference. I think European history has never really taken that division in very much. They hadn\rquote t realised, that until we got to 1880, or to ... (?? \endash 
 35.40) in France, these countries we
re completely divided from the point of view of access to literacy and access to a pencil and paper, so the oral culture, what everyone thinks about it, was certainly devalued to the point of view of getting into jobs of one kind or another, radically.

