\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. Well, she was a sociologist first of all. Her father was a very important social psychologist called Newcomb, and she had worked with Al Gouldner, in the States, but she wanted to do anthropology, and she came over to work with Meyer Fortes, and she 
came \endash 
 we both went to Ghana together, in the second fieldwork that I did, and we went out there at least twice, if not more frequently. And I had three children by my first wife, and two by Esther, and went out, with them, and she became very attached to N
orthern Ghana and is working there now, and worked there for many years. Yes, she was an anthropologist too, or a sociologist and anthropologist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
