When I went to see these other people, the LoDagaba, I was very interested in some remark, which I think \endash  I\rquote m not sure if it was a Frenchman or Rattray \endash  had made about the Ashanti, that in these matrilineal systems, that the sister
\rquote s son \endash  the nephew \endash  was waiting for the apple to die, so that he could inherit his goods. So I was very interested to see whether there was further tension between the two, in that way. But I didn\rquote 
t have any instruments to pick it up. That was one thing that interested me, just as when I went down to the Gonja, which was the second tribe that I went to with Esther Goody, I was very interested in the succession system, and how this affected people
\rquote s view of the predecessor, depending on whether he was the next of kin, waiting for the next of kin to die \endash  as in the case of Prince Charles \endash  or if it was one of th
ese systems, as in the Gonja, where each next ruler, had to come from a different group, a different sub-group, and t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid15413545 here had to be what I called a \lquote 
rotational succession\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , as in the United Nations and various other places, where you move from one to the o
ther. I wanted to see if in those systems, there was any less tension between, for example, father and son, than there was in the others. So that was always behind there. That was behind my interest in that. I don\rquote 
t know that I ever made it very clear, and certainly very few psychologists will regard that as being psychological, but I did.
