\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. I was. I did think that there were some things in which you could repeat informati
on and hand it down over time, and I think to some extent Vansina was okay in terms of royal dynastic records in that way, and I recorded, myself, a few in Ashanti, which were repeated by remembrances. But by and large, I thought that insufficient attenti
on had been paid to the fact that if you were recounting a myth, as distinct from a dynastic history, if you were recounting myth, and it was a long recitation, that you couldn\rquote 
t remember this exactly, and that you were liable to fill in passages that you couldn\rquote 
t remember, and to re-create the passage. And I thought the aspect of creation, of creating literature in simple societies, was very much underplayed. As I say, there was no reason why people should repeat the same thing over and over again, and if t
hey couldn\rquote t remember it, they would make something else up at the time \endash 
 and that seemed, to me, what was happening. Perhaps not with dynastic memory so much, but even there I was pretty suspicious of inexact recordings over time. I tried to do this with historical records in the Gonja, and I\rquote 
ve never written them up in any sense.
