t think of as simply being repetitions of a previous generation, as many people did. Otherwise how would you get such a flourishing of different cultures in Africa, where you\rquote 
ve got some 8,000 different groups near one another? No, you get a transformation of culture, a flourishing of culture, just as you get a flourishing of languages. Just as language doesn\rquote t remain the same between here and my mother\rquote 
s native Aberdeenshire, in which I found, to my horror, recently, that I couldn\rquote t understand a word, even though they\rquote 
re speaking Anglo-Saxon and not Celtic! But they are deviated from Anglo-Saxon as spoken in the area, they deviated a thousand years ago, or 1500 years ago, so they spoke a very different language. And I think it\rquote 
s the same with culture, with these local cultures. That\rquote s what we think of writing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8086691  (??)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , of the LoDagabas going back infinitely, is probably a mistake. It\rquote s much more flexible, much more flexible than that. Anyhow, you asked me about comparative work.
