ve always thought that that was terrible, but when I see efforts to get out of that, I\rquote ve not always been satisfied. But that\rquote 
s because I, myself, would like to be able to pick and choose. I like to be able to do my historical work, at the same as the anthropological or sociological work, so at one level I see them very much linked up. But I can see there\rquote 
s another level by which you might want to join those people who want to spend their lives looking at a village society, and those who want to spend their
 lives looking at some factory organisation, so I think there might be some rationale for a division of that kind. But I think, intellectually, it\rquote 
s not very satisfactory, and I think [there are] links between the two, at different levels. Some [sociologists] like George Homans [could be] doing a factory study along quasi-anthropological lines, and I think there are many more ties. You know, there
\rquote s got to be cross-cutting ties between these fields, even if you do think that fieldwork of an intensive character is critical in the one, and not so critical in the other \endash 
 the other is more statistical, more numerical in that way. But I do feel one ought to be looking for links at an intellectual level. One ought to be looking for links between the disciplines: e
ven if, as a discipline, psychology does require different things from sociology, nevertheless there is a point at which these things link up. I suppose it\rquote 
s because of that that I, like Peter Laslett, was so much in favour of starting Social and Political Sciences in Cambridge.
