\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16667799 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I think at a certain time, mainly as a result of working with linguistics applied to anthropology, especially in the work of L\'e9
vi-Strauss, in whi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16667799 ch the whole business of \lquote binary contrasts\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  was blown up and made the key to understanding particular groups, you got these attempts to pr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16667799 oduce columns \endash  usually headed \lquote Male\rquote  or \lquote Female\rquote , \lquote Left\rquote , \lquote Right\rquote , \lquote Sun\rquote , \lquote Moon\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , something like this \endash  as if that summed up the total context of society. And it had a complicated arrangement too, complicated matter to do with L\'e9vi-Strauss
\rquote s concept of structure, which led in various directions, but one of them was to do with these forms of binary division. They were particularly associated with the professor in Oxford \endash  [Rodney] Needham \endash 
 in this country and I found this very trivial. Not that there isn\rquote t some aspect of it which is perfectly correct, we know that we\rquote re in wrong position with the left ha
nd, and the right with the right hand, and that sort of thing, but it didn\rquote 
t allow enough for ambiguity. The fact, for example, that a xylophone player among the LoDagaba was always known as a left-handed man, because his left hand was as important as his 
right in playing the xylophone, as a piano player, and, therefore, he was assumed }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16667799 to have female characteristics.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I didn\rquote t see, at all, this was necessarily true. There was this tendency to say in the two columns, this binary opposition, that black was op
posed to white, that black was associated with night, with witchcraft, and with women, and various things, whereas I thought that the use of language, and the use of thought, was much more flexible than that. That you had to be prepared to think that blac
k was not only witchcraft, but was also beautiful, under circumstances, especially in Africa, so black was \endash 
 the black rain cloud, or the black earth was what you wanted, for fertility. It was not simply negative, and to be associated with witchcraft and so on. So I thought that much too facile. Fortunately it\rquote 
s a form of analysis which had its day, and which is no longer in fashion. That is what I meant by binary analysis.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16667799   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I don\rquote t mean that I didn\rquote t see any gross divisions between, say, literate accounts a
nd purely oral ones. I think that is, again, is simplified in the sense that means of communication are always adding on to one another, that is to say literacy, writing adds on to oral communication, just as electronic communication adds on to writing. I
t doesn\rquote 
t displace the book, it adds on to the book and makes it more complicated. It modifies the book, just as to my mind, the existence of reading and writing modified orality, so that the oral in post-Bronze Age societies, was never the same as the oral
 in earlier societies. You\rquote ve always got to look at the oral in our society as being \endash  important as it is \endash  as being related to the literate as well. That is, it doesn\rquote 
t exist on its own, it exists in relation to the literate, so that there are contexts in
 which literate communication is considered appropriate, and others in which oral communication is appropriate. But even then the oral one is influenced by the literate communication. So that\rquote 
s what I meant really, in saying that I was against the sort of analysis that L\'e9vi-Strauss not only made there, but also in his posing of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
La Pens\'e9e Sauvage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  and other forms of thought, because I thought that although there was an important difference between the two, what he didn
\rquote t look at was how you got from one to the other \endash  in historical terms \endash  and also how one added on to the other, in terms of literature for example. And I thought he didn\rquote 
t pay enough attention to the fact that when he talked about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 La Pens\'e9e Sauvage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , what he\rquote s talking about was oral communication largely, and that had various characteristics, various limitations which didn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16667799 \rquote t exist in literate societies.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But that\rquote s all I meant. I didn\rquote 
t mean that you couldn\rquote t \endash  because I, myself, have seen societies very much as divided, for example, by the plough
. The introduction of the plough in the part of Africa where I was, seemed, to me, enormously important. That is to say, instead of hoeing up some patch of land the size of the courtyard here, which is all you could do with a hoe, that when you used anima
l traction and put a plough behind an ox or a horse, you could go from here right to Newport or further in one ploughing operation.
