\rquote t 
getting in the areas of Africa that I was working in, because you will always find a man, a more distant man, in the same clan, say a cousin, who would inherit, rather than a woman. So we never got the situations that you got in Europe and Asia, of the wo
man inheriting the property and bringing a man in to marry, yes, to bring a man in, like Prince Philip or someone coming in. I mean, that would be inconceivable. That was very intere}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1529417 sting to me that that happened.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I related that a bit to the fact that unde
r the relatively egalitarian system in Africa \endash  not always egalitarian by any means \endash  but it didn\rquote t matter much who you married, but it mattered very much in Europe and Asia, and what a wif}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
