s son, but it\rquote s always to a male, so the woman is not, herself, independent. Whereas you can argue that in Europe and Asia, a woman who is an heiress, as in Ancient Greece, is important
 in her own right, and for the property she owns, and therefore she can attract somebody to marry her. You see, if you\rquote re an heiress \endash  and this made a lot of difference \endash 
 if you were an heiress in Ancient Greece, you had to marry your cousin, as in an Arab marriage \endash  your father\rquote s brother\rquote s son \endash  you had to marry, because you didn\rquote 
t want the property to go out of the family, and that was because the woman had a right to that property. Before it went to a more distant cousin, it went downward to her, before it went sideways an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid216898 d out to a more distant cousin.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
So I think that one has to be very careful about matrilineal societies. It\rquote s true there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid216898 are some which are what I call \lquote matriarchal\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  in that sense, in which the woman has the power, and her property goes 
to other women. But this is not the case with matrilineal societies in Africa, I think. Audrey Richards did a very interesting article about this in the Congo, and as I recall, all of the matrilineal societies she dealt with there, it goes to the woman, a
nd it\rquote s not a question of dividing up the land as they did in Europe, so that the woman has something to go into marriage with, for example, you don\rquote t get a dowry system with that kind, although it\rquote s called dowry, mainly }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid216898 through the French idea of the \lquote dot\rquote . Although they call it \lquote dowry\rquote , the \lquote bridewealth\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
