t always work out that way. Sometimes the husband, who generally controls it, pinches it, but in most law codes, the dowry goes back to the woman, and this is quite different from Africa, because nothing comes down. As a father, you don\rquote 
t give anything. Your daughter, when she marries, there\rquote s the bridewealth coming in rather than dowry going out. I think you get this business of the woman inheriting, to my mind, in Eurasian societies, where you\rquote 
ve got a more economically stratified system where it matters who you marry. If you\rquote ve got one of these egalitarian systems, or relatively egalitarian, it doesn\rquote t matter much who you marry \endash 
