 18.31), and whatever the other Anglo-Saxon terms were. Often, they failed to distinguish them, they made the situation much more bilateral, as we called it, than it was before. I was interested in that, but I was as interested i
n the fact that in early Europe, that every Will that you found, every Anglo-Saxon Will you found, left something to the Church. So I was very interested that women were leaving to the Church, for example, and men, too, were leaving property to the Church
, and that writing was involved in this. If you were going to alienate }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5376739 (??) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
