t sufficient to do, as my friends in Northern Congo have done, just to know that you own the land for ever and ever. You had to have a piece of paper to show you that you had passed this land on to somebody else, and that seemed, to me, very important 
\endash  important from the point of view of the written word, and important from the point of view of the transfer of land outside the kinship group to the Church. Because what I found very amazing really \endash  and still do \endash 
 was that already by 800, it\rquote s been estimated a third of the arable land in Western Eu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12672073 rope was in the Church\rquote s hands.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 So I was interested to know how that could happen, that the Church could build up such a large estate, and probably from nothing \endash  obviously the Christian Church 
\endash  and what had happened to the inheritance system in
