 Church\rquote s hand, so you got these various laws to do with not being able to transfer landed property, anyhow, to the Church, any longer, because it was in the dead hands of the Church. [Which] meant that it never circulated any longer \endash 
 it never moved, it was in the Church\rquote s hands, and that\rquote s where it sat \endash  so that you got the move, of course, to not to endow the Church in that way, but to endowing the Masses, an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12672073 d parts the great English call \lquote tradition\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, that flourishes here and elsewhere is partly through t
his aspect of mortmain and the inability to give land to the Church, or for the Church to acquire more land than it had already. Anyhow, this is one of the things I was playing around with, in that little book.
