\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes. Very much. Well, the village I was in depended mo
stly on another small town further away, which is where my friend, Kum, went to school. He was in the first group of schoolboys at that school. And, incidentally, I think the book, it\rquote 
s partly interesting to show how authoritarian these schools were. No do
ubt schools in general were, when you think about the Mesopotamian school and Big Brother and so on, and what it meant to him to have his so-called illiterate brothers running around the fields, looking after the cows, in freedom, while he had to be shut 
up in some classroom for all his life. He resented this. He ran away. And didn\rquote t like the discipline. You had to exert the discipline, in a sense, to ke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2098327 
ep somebody in this small room.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But in the village I was in \endash  that had affected Kum by then, because he was sent away to school \endash 
 they\rquote d just started a school not long before I was there, and I was interested to see what the initial uses of literacy were in that community. There were funerals going on, which I went to, incessantly, and at some of these funer
als a schoolboy, or an ex-schoolboy, would be having to write down what gifts came in, and what gifts went out. Now, if you can imagine that in a purely oral situation beforehand, you wouldn\rquote 
t remember, when the next funeral came, whether Uncle Fred had or had not given you a chicken at that time. Maybe you would give him the benefit of the doubt and say, \'93That was my uncle. He must have given me a chicken, because he\rquote s my uncle\'94
. But if you had a schoolboy writing this down, you\rquote ve seen that Uncle Fred perhaps didn\rquote t have a chicken on that day. So what are you going to do next time? You look up this written document, you say, \'93Well, he didn\rquote 
t give me one then, so I won\rquote t give him one now\'94, you become much more precise in your reciprocity by having a written document, and you don\rquote 
t think so much in terms of relationships, as in terms of the individual who did it. But I thought that was interesting, because it seemed to make reciprocity much more precise \endash  like keeping a track of who sent you a Christmas card 
last year, so that you could send the same this year, not thinking, \'93I should send one to my brother or uncle\'94 or something, but \'93X sent me one, I should send X one\'94.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2098327  So it differed on reciprocity.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Then again, when I was there, there was an Improvement So
ciety started. Most of these villages were starting Improvement Societies, initiated by schoolboys, or people who had been to school, to bring their community into the modern age \endash 
 however that was described. But what was interesting to me was the fact tha
t people kept records of these meetings, and they elected a Chairman and Secretary too, and they kept records of meetings, so that when the next meeting took place, they would look up these records and say, \'93Have we done that?\'94
 Now, can you imagine that happening in an oral society? No, you couldn\rquote t! People wouldn\rquote t have that exact ... you know, precise recording of things brought back to them, and saying, \'93Where do we go from here?\'94
 which was a huge advantage, I\rquote m sure, in making things move. But if you we
re simply looking back in a purely oral way from your memory, there would be a tendency to forget to see things as they are now, rather than as they were six months ago. So that, too, was, to my mind, interesting, and that was at the village level.
