\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, but I wasn\rquote 
t working on that. No. I mean, I was, because I spent some time in China, and whenever I got a chance, I went \endash  in Japan \endash  to a Chinese restaurant, because I thought Japanese food was very precious, being served up \endash  I mean, I was 
taken to various meals where it was served up by these geishas, who present you with food on a plate, and when you got this soup, it was said to be made with some sort of herb taken from Mount Fuji. Well if the Japanese could tell the difference, I couldn
\rquote t! And it seemed to me that it was an elaboration of merchant cuisine which was going too elaborate, incredibly elaborate. And I must say I much preferred Chinese food to Japanese food. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So in terms of the empirical information on food, am I right that you looked at your notes from Ghana?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid9920776 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes. I don\rquote t think that I had been to Japan at that time. I don\rquote t think even I had been to China. I\rquote 
d eaten a lot in Chinese restaurants, and I\rquote d spent time in India, but food, certainly Chinese home food, and Japanese home food, I didn\rquote 
t really experience those until later. In any case, what interested me broadly was this class aspect of food, the fact that in Africa, you broadly had classes or you had sex groups which didn\rquote t differentiate in terms of havin}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6180633 g the same food.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
And therefore that affected the marriage system, because you married anybody from any group, and one of the things that interested me about the marriage system, which I wrote about quite early on, is that basically there was no tendency the
re for endogamy \endash  for marrying within \endash 
 which is what you got in Europe and in Asia, a tendency always to marry in. In India, of course, you had to marry in, it was obligatory, but elsewhere you got a strong tendency to marry within the same socio-economic
 or same class, which in Africa you didn\rquote t get. In fact, I distinctly remember somebody said to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6180633 me in the state (?? \endash  26.32 ??) }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 society in Africa, a member of the ruling class telling me, \'93We don\rquote t marry our sisters, we don\rquote t want to marry our sisters. They\rquote re too }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1585847 proud. We marry somebody else\'94.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
Anyhow, politically, it made a difference, because you didn\rquote t get a society stratified into groups in the same way. You got a lot of cross-cutting ties, because a chief would have, among his wives, a variety of wiv
es, but would have one from this group and one from that group, and that, to my mind, made a lot of difference to the political system, as distinct from when you got a clear division between these groups. Also it meant there was no great cultural division
 between these various classes. That is to say they weren\rquote t differentiated to any great extent. Obviously they were to a little, but to any great extent they were not subcultures, whereas in Europe and in Asia \endash  in China or India \endash 
 you got these in-marrying groups.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9920776   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
As Marc Bloch has said, with regards to some rural group in France, that once you saw these intermarrying group[s], that was the beginning of a class, it was certainly the beginning of a subculture, because they had their own cultural patterns, a
nd they were marrying somebody from the same group, which wasn\rquote t the case in Africa, except in the lakes, in Rwanda and around there.
