\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Did you learn any non-European ways of cooking?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Oh yes. I certainly cooked Indian food, and African food. But African food was no great shakes! I mean, porridge, which my mother lived on, was not my favourite dish in a hot climate!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
I think one of the books mentions you\rquote ve been to Indonesia and Bali, and was interested by that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. I was interested in food in Bali, of course, but I don\rquote t think I did much about it when I was there. I wasn\rquote 
t there for very long. My first interest was the fact that in Africa, people were eating more or less the same sort of thing, whereas in Europe, what you were eating in a cottage, and what you were eating in 
a merchant house, were something very different. And what I was really interested in was the difference between }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 haute cuisine}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8609456  and, by implication, a \lquote Basque\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
 cuisine, and the fact that you got something from an }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 haute cuisine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  which I thought you didn\rquote t get in Africa. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And you also found Basque cuisine in Australia, I think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Very much so.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Can you say something about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, not very much really, except that I\rquote d say that was interesting, but when I was there things were changing so much. But I have a cookbook somewhere \endash  I don\rquote t know whether it\rquote s here \endash 
 on Australian cooking, which was really flapjacks and this kind of thing, it was very basic sort of Basque cuisine. High cuisine turned out to be of course, in Chinatown, which when I was there, was growing very rapidly \endash 
 Chinatown, you went down there to have your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 haute cuisine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 . I\rquote m sure that there were some areas in Australia which did marginally have something 
better, and certainly some of these immigrants from Yugoslavia and so on, were starting restaurants, which were a bit better. But I thought that Australia was very marked by its cuisine at that time, certainly among the Anglos. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab What about the Abori
gines?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab The Aborigines that I met 
\endash  because I didn\rquote t work on the Aborigines \endash  the Aborigines in Sydney were, of course, the lowest of the low \endash  I mean, very working class lives they led \endash  and I can\rquote t believe they\rquote d been brought }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8609456 up on those Missions in Armrand }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 (?? \endash 
 34.39) or wherever, that they don\rquote t do any cooking at all in those Missions. Missionary food from Africa, from my experience in Africa, was pretty basic, though I did have one great surprise in Africa: I went across into a French-speaking c
ountry in the Upper Volta at one time, and there, French clerics were living on a much higher level than their English counterparts were. The English counterparts seemed, to me, to be living on the same kind of diets that my mother lived on in Scotland, p
erhaps not local porridge, but the next least extravagant thing to that. They were, after all, Protestant, and did not believe in luxury, and for luxuries you had to go elsewhere, and not to a Protestant household \endash 
 these missionary households, Baptists and so on, missionaries.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Now, another slightly different question. You\rquote ve linked up food and sex and love, why is there a connection between food and love or sex?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, food is very simple, I thought, in Africa. You go into a compound, like a square \endash  like we have out here \endash 
 and you see people preparing their meals, and as I said to you, they may come from these different groups in the society, some of whom are chieftain groups, some are merchant groups, some are others, but they\rquote re cooking in fr
ont of their sleeping houses, and pounding up food and cooking, and there\rquote 
s not much cultural difference in that. And as for the recipes, if there are differences, [they are] to be exchanged between each other, and therefore soon the whole lot will be homo
genised. And there was homogeneity in culture in that way that you were getting, which you do not get in societies where you had an upstairs and downstairs system, and where you married somebody from your same group, an endogenous marriage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab So when 
you talk about food and love, you really mean food and marriage? You\rquote re not talking about sexuality and food?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab No. No, I\rquote 
m not talking sexuality in that sense. No, I\rquote m talking about food and love which leads to marriage. Yes. Well, in a sense there i
s an aspect of love, there is an aspect of love in it, in that demographers talk very much about love marriages, and one significant thing for them, in Western Europe, was a free choice of marriage \endash 
 a love marriage in that sense. So freedom of choice in that. But I felt that even where you got that possibility in Europe, nevertheless the number of arranged marriages you get \endash  see Jane Austen \endash 
 was pretty high. Arranged marriages between members of the same class, and it\rquote s quite true that you may have sligh
tly more freedom of choice, but the level of choice was restricted. And in Africa you got much more arrangement in marriage, more arrangement of marriage, but you certainly got the possibility of people making a free choice, especially in second marriages
, of which you got a very high level, because you got frequent divorce in most cases. And so love in that sense \endash  in the sense of free choice of partner \endash 
 certainly did exist there, even though, in many cases marriages were arranged, in the sense that, you know, you had to marry your second cousin, or something like that. But then if you think of, again, of Jane Austen\rquote s day, the beginning of the 19
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  century, there\rquote 
s a good deal more arrangement in marriage in Europe. So I didn\rquote t think it was all that diffe
rent. There was some difference, but certainly not the difference that Malthus or others would make between prescription on one side, and freedom on the other. This idea, you know, that we are free and everybody else is in bonds, did not seem to be true. 
And that the link of that was capitalism, it seemed to me very very frail. It\rquote s certainly true that there\rquote s more choice in some areas and less choice in others, but it wasn\rquote t a difference between choice and no choice at all \endash 
 a difference of degree, in that sense \endash  just as freedom itself, as far as there are differences in degree, and not of freedom on one side and constraint on another. I thought that was the wrong way of putting it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes. And you say, in 
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Food and Love}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 , you say, \'93
In Black Africa, generally one does not find much development of a discourse of love\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Yes, because I was ver}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5767801 y impressed with the fact that \lquote discourse of love\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  arose very often in poetry, or in letter writing to somebody at a distance. You do not normally go up to your wife and say, \'93I love you\'94
, but if she went away for a month or two, you wrote this in a letter, and I thought the elaboration of discourse in writing happened much more in Europe and Asia than it did in Africa, that you got the elaboration of a discourse of love \endash 
 a discourse in the sense of writing down to somebody at a distance \endash  and that most love poetry was to somebody at a distance, whether i
t was here or in Ancient Egypt or in China, it was to a soldier gone off to the war, or something like this, or something at a distance. That seemed to me an occasion for an elaboration of discourse of love, or it might be, as in pursuing a romance with s
omebody distanced from you socially, you\rquote 
re elaborating this discourse. And it seemed to be that in Africa, in a purely oral context, in a purely oral context, that there was less occasion for this kind of elaboration of emotion than you got in Europe or in Asia.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
How would they express emotion, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, they would certainly express it verbally, but one has to remember that all of oral contact is face-to-face, never anything else, so you say it to somebody, \'93I want you\'94, or something like that. Or, \'93Will you be my lover?\'94
 or something like this. But it\rquote s very much a face-to-face contact, it\rquote s not the impersonal contact that comes through letter writing, so that if you move away to another town, there\rquote s nothing you can say to your wife that you\rquote 
ve left behind. You can\rquote t elaborate a discourse to her in any sense, in that way. It just has to remain dormant, or internalised, if you like. I\rquote 
m not saying that one is stronger than another, or I think you could talk yourself into certain things, but you haven\rquote t got any way of communicating that love at a distance, at a social distance, you can only do it in face-to-face situations.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab So you wouldn\rquote 
t argue that you have to have a discourse of love to have the feelings of love?
