\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
It would be nice if you could say something about the experience of teaching in Cambridge, which I think you did from 1954 to 1984. Is that right?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2315495 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Something like that, yes. Well, when I began teaching here, it was really \endash  my
 supervisor at Oxford, Meyer Fortes came over here to be professor, and he started things, doing things completely differently, because before that time the subject had been taught in a rather haphazard and amateur way \endash 
 one topic here and one topic there. But Fortes was very anxious to teach in a Malinowskian way, well, about social structure, and to teach systematically about the economy and policy, religion and kinship. So that I had to lecture, whe}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid14099631 n I came, on one of the topics.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The one I was given a l
ecture on, I can remember, was politics and law, so I had to read up an enormous amount about primitive law, which I did first of all, which was quite useful to me when I was re-doing my thesis. So I lectured on primitive law, and on policy, but law, but 
after that \endash  I\rquote d done that when I was the most junior person on the block \endash 
 after that, as my status increased, I could choose what topic, and I lectured on religion, because well, my thesis was on that. And I guess I lectured, eventually, on matters to do 
with kinship ... kinship, in those days, was always the high status thing to lecture about, and since I had Fortes and Leach ahead of me, and probably some others as well, I didn\rquote t get to lecture on that very often, but occasionally I}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4145098  did. And gradually I expanded.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But I didn\rquote 
t really lecture on any of the subjects I\rquote ve talked to you about. I don\rquote t think I ever even lectured on literacy, even though I worked on that. I may have done. I must have lectured on communication somewhere along the line, but I cer
tainly didn\rquote t make a thing of it. And I don\rquote t think I had any students who were interested in, or who wanted to work on it afterwards. They all wanted to do traditional anthropological fieldwork \endash  going working in a village somewhere 
\endash  and they weren\rquote t very interested. Even those who went to work in India \endash  and it was always something that I was sorry about with anthropologists \endash  were not really interested in, or capable, should I say, of working on the li}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495 terary aspects of the language.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 Even anthropologist
s who went to work in China, until recently \endash  a lot of them didn\rquote t know the written language. I don\rquote t think my friend, Maurice Freedman, who was professor at LSE and Oxford, ever knew written Chinese. I\rquote 
m not sure. But that always seemed to me a great error, if we confine ourselves to oral communication in that way, without taking into account these other levels, that\rquote 
s partly what I was interested in, in India, is the way the two levels interacted with the written religion and how that worked out locally i
n an oral context. And how something like the Sanskrit tradition got handed down. So that was part of what I was interested in there. But you couldn\rquote t teach that in anthropological courses, you had to teach what I spoke to you about before \endash 
 face-to-face interaction, essentially.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
How did you teach people to go to a village in Africa, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, when I became professor, I introduced various postgraduate courses, before it went into the field, and what did I introduce? One was language learning
. Another was the techniques of fieldwork and writing notes and so on, and that was done before, because Malinowski, himself, was rather hot on that with his students. That is, he taught them to write certain notes with a red pencil, and certain ones with
 a blue pencil and so on \endash  I\rquote m not quite sure how he did this, but Audrey Richards used to lecture on that \endash  systematically keeping field notes, and keeping a feel of [the] census too, the census material.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
What do these different colours signify?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I don\rquote 
t remember. But I do know that I never used it, I never used that system, but I did keep different sorts of records. I kept my field notes, I kept a diary, and I kept sets of material, or accounts of different houses in the village, which were on
 different sheets of paper.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab What, that\rquote 
s more like survey material, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes. But because I used to send, on the back of the forms, writing down things about them, about the house, that I knew, but essentially, yes, you\rquote re right, it was 
survey material. But that I built up over time, because I got worried once over material. I know a friend in the village, that I spoke to almost every day I was there, and drank at his house frequently, and I remember, after a long time he made }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495 a reference to somebody as his \lquote in-law\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, and I said, \'93Good God! What do you mean \lquote in-law\rquote ? You weren\rquote t married there\'94. And it turned out, when I\rquote 
d got all this data on divorce and so on, that he had married there, and I never knew about it. But he had no children by this wife, so there was no reference point to cling on to this either for me or for him. And I thought, \'93
Good God! If this person, whom I knew so well, I still didn\rquote t know his past history, what don\rquote t I know of anybody else?\'94 So ideas about divorces, for example, I thought useless after that, or virtually, because it didn\rquote 
t show all this. All I could tell with divorces and relationship to children, that I could see in front of me in the village, I simply could not trust the data on saying, \'93Do you remember so and so?\'94 because they didn\rquote t, or didn\rquote 
t want to remember. I didn\rquote t get that. My data would have been very inaccurate on that kind of thing. Fortunately I don\rquote t think I ever wanted to publish on that particular matter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
But were students ever taught about interviewing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, if I did, it wasn
\rquote t in a very very systematic way. I suppose I did. I was always worried about that, because if you said, \'93Are these your children?\'94 and counted them, you could not be sure that they weren\rquote t a brother\rquote s child, or something lik}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495 e that, because the same word, \lquote child\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
, would be used for a brother\rquote s child as your own, and so you rather got this situation, as you might in England, with saying, \'93We\rquote re t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495 
alking about your aunt\'94 \endash  your \lquote aunt\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  just being a friend of your mother\rquote s or something like that. It wasn\rquote 
t really a correct kinship term in that sense, rather it wasn\rquote t understood in the sense that you understood a different sense to the individual. I don\rquote t think that affected my ordinary demographic data very 
much, but I could easily see how it could affect it, and particularly going around to stranger houses, and these are houses I knew very well, because I went down there every day and walked around them. But, no, I didn\rquote 
t really do anything about the interviewing techniques, I just \endash  to tell you the truth, in those days, I probably thought it came naturally.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
And you would talk about your experiences, though, to the students, would you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Not ver
y much, no. Very little, because there was so much difference, depending on where you were going, and I wouldn\rquote 
t trust my information to be of much value to anyone else, quite honestly. It reminds me of somebody I was a student with here, who went for an interview to get a Scholarship from the Treasury at one time, and as someone saying, \'93
Yes, Mr. So and So. And what is your major problem in doing this fieldwork?\'94 He turned round and said, \'93How do I know until I get there, what my problem is?\'94 Well, anthropology was a bit like that in those days. You didn\rquote 
t sort something out beforehand, you went there to find out. I knew, roughly, that I was going somewhere that had a system which was partly matrilineal and partly patrilineal \endash  I knew that before I went \endash  but I don\rquote 
t think there was anyone that could have told me much that would have been useful about how to proceed when I got there, not unless you happened to have been going to an Indian village, that would have been different, because I could have told the
m what I knew about the Indian village. But I don\rquote t think it would have helped very much in that situation. In any case, whether or not it did, I didn\rquote 
t do very much about that. But usually, when I organised this course, I did do one on the fieldwork methods, and I did get somebody to teach something on approaches to fieldwork, though I never taught it myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Now, in 1966, you became Director of African Studies, I think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab That\rquote 
s right. Well, it made a big difference to me, personally, because I had my own independent unit. I was still a member of the same Department, just, although Fortes wasn\rquote t very pleased with me doing this. But I did at the time because I got a Smuts
\rquote  Readership, that\rquote s it, nobody seemed likely to promote me to Readership, so I thought I ought to put in for this one. So I did, but he wasn\rquote t very pleased about that. But anyhow, I did keep in the Department, and I gave my lectures.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Why was he not pleased that you were getting a Readership, then?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid2315495 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid14356576 Well, there were 
two things I think. Firstly, the person that had had this position before me, was an anthropologist who had been at LSE at the same time as Fortes, and was a pupil of Malinowski, and a great friend of Malinowski\rquote s \endash  Audrey Richards \endash 
 and she was here for t
his. And Fortes made a great thing of African Studies, and this was an African Studies Centre, and Fortes and his colleagues, like Evans-Pritchard and so on, and Radcliffe-Brown, never thought much of regional studies, and they thought anthropology ought 
to be like economics, and generalise the subject, which wasn\rquote t tied to one particular area. If I may say so, that\rquote s the reason that economics has difficulty, particularly development economics in Africa, for example, because they don\rquote 
t understand the local situation differs from the situation in India for examp}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495\charrsid14356576 le. And so they were not happy.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid14356576 I remember when they started the African Studies Association in Britain, Fortes and Evans-Pritchard who were two of the first foremost Africanists, wouldn\rquote 
t join, and they didn\rquote t join this one. They were rather unhappy to see Regional Studies expand, which it did at a certain time, because that meant an expansion for their subject, but they weren\rquote 
t at all keen on African Studies as distinct from Indian Studies, and also, the teaching that I, myself, got from these people, at Oxford particularly \endash 
 was not limited to one area. You read a monograph about India, you read one about China, and providing they were written by a student of Malinowski, you were all right! But you didn\rquote 
t only concentrate on Africa. We did, in my generation, largely concentrate on Africa, because most of the money was available to do fieldwork in Africa at that time, to do work in Africa. So he wasn\rquote 
t very pleased about that, for general grants, and he also wasn\rquote t very happy about Audrey Richards\rquote  activities when she got here.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2315495\charrsid14356576   
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid14356576 
But it did give me a certain amount of independence, and I ran a seminar at that time, which [resulted in] my first book on literacy, the book that came out as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid14356576 Literacy in Traditional Societies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid14356576 
 [ed. 1968], which I got a number of people to write for and give papers, and the paper that Watt and I had written. Now, that I did from the African Studies Centre, that was not from Anthropology. I could never have done a seminar like tha
t in Anthropology, I did it under African Studies, where I was the boss, and could do what I wanted to.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I\rquote 
m really surprised that you wouldn\rquote t have been able to do it in Anthropology.
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13578640 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I never tried. I don\rquote t think I ever tried. I think t
hat in that period after the War, anthropology that was carried out in societies with written culture, like India and China, but you didn\rquote 
t acknowledge the written culture, you pretended that everything was all the same as Africans ... As I say, anthropologists did not normally learn a learned language, even though it may have been important in the locality \endash  they didn\rquote 
t learn Chinese in that way. They had done originally, but that seemed to have changed. But at that time, they didn\rquote t. And I think the idea 
of you going off, like Malinowski, perhaps one forgets how important the influence of Malinowski was on these people, the idea of dumping yourself in a society and looking at some technical process or other that\rquote 
s being done there, and then building up from that, and learning a language, not from books but from i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13578640 nteraction, was very important.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I think I said that when I came back here first of all, I wanted to do fieldwork in Europe, because of my wartime experiences, but there was no money for fieldwork i
n Europe at the time. Well, I did apply to do fieldwork in Europe, before I\rquote d done my Ph.D., I applied for a job doing a survey, a rural survey in Dorset.
