\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, when you becam
e Director of African Studies, did you broaden out the field?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, yes. Because I conducted that seminar with a friend of mine, a sociologist here \endash  Edward Shils and I had this seminar in African Studies, and that broadened out, and I didn\rquote t care a
t the time, whether it was Africa or where it was. There was sufficient of Africa in it to make it ... It was interdisciplinary too. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
