\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Yes, I think it was, probably. I mean, there
 was very little that went on in that period. I can remember when I first produced that volume and sent it to Cambridge University Press, the Syndics turned it down because it jumped from one subject to another. It was only a friend of mine that I knew, M
ichael Black, an editor who knew Ian Watt, and he said saved it from extinction, from it being chucked out. So I did eventually get it published by them, but they weren\rquote t happy at first, because they thought, \'93
Which discipline does this fall into?\'94 And I was anxious not to have it fall into any discipline. So that\rquote s what I could do at African Studies. I mean, I could do what I wanted there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
