 place in Poland, and did a lot of fieldwork. His wife is Hungarian. And [then] he went to Turkey and did fieldwork in a tea plantation in Northern Turkey when she was working there, and 
he also has been, for quite a while, to North China, to Urumchi, up in the North of China, he\rquote s been working on Chinese, so he\rquote s done a lot. But he\rquote 
s now in Halle, in charge of the Max Planck Institute, there in Germany. He was at Sussex, and before that h
e was here, had a lectureship and fellowship at Corpus Christi. In fact, wanted to come back to England recently, and he put in for the Chair in Anthropology recently, when Marilyn Strathern left, and I was very cross because he wasn\rquote 
t even short-listed \endash  it seemed to me extraordinary that somebody who had done that amount of fieldwork \endash  I mean, he\rquote 
s done more fieldwork than any half a dozen anthropologists you can mention, and has been head of the very prestigious German Institute. Anyhow, he\rquote s much better off where he is because he\rquote 
s got a lot of money there, he can go wherever he wants, and get assistance for this and that. But he wanted to come here. He also wanted to go to Oxford, but there they appointed Gellner\rquote s son, which was not a bad appointment, but ...
