\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab No. I certainly don\rquote 
t miss lecturing. Perhaps giving seminars, I quite like doing. I still get \endash  in France, for example, where they\rquote re more interested in communications, I get asked to give lectures in France quite frequently, whereas I don\rquote 
t think, in this country, I\rquote ve ever been asked to talk about literacy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab That\rquote 
s amazing!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I don\rquote 
t think so. I wouldn\rquote t swear to that, but I don\rquote t remember it. But in France, I frequently get asked. I went down to Lyon, Juliet and I were down there quite recent
ly, in June, when I went down to give a talk on some aspects of literacy. But it\rquote s usually in France these days, if I get asked to do some.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
So during these years, you developed all sorts of new ideas. Where were the important contexts for discussing those ideas and refining them?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12585883 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I can\rquote t say they were self-generating, it wasn\rquote 
t true they were altogether self-generating, but the stuff with literacy obviously arose out of my contact originally with Ian Watt, and then I just went on thinkin
g about different aspects of literacy. I suppose I was asked to talk about them, mainly in France and elsewhere. They didn\rquote t come about \endash 
 to talk about them in an anthropological context. I may have talked about them a bit more in a sociological one with Edward Shils, for example, but as far as the ones about East and West are concerned, and Europe and Asia and Africa, once again it
\rquote s been ... When you asked me that question, I think, with regard to Africa, it\rquote s really being asked to write something about i
n Africa, for example, and what are the main features of endogamy or exogamy. I mean, the general ideas are floating around. I think I put them in place in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12585883 
Africa and Asia, in that sense.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 About East and West, I was stimulated, I think, in that on the dome
stic front, on the front of [relationships] and domestic life, I was stimulated by my friend, Peter Laslett, and the work which the Cambridge Group did, so that probably partially arose out of nattering with them. So I think that the Cambridge Group was i
m
portant in that, and also, to some extent, in thinking about what was different about Europe from Asia. Because an old member of the Cambridge Group, Tony Wrigley, was very much concerned with that. He was concerned with Holland and England, and what made
 
them special, which I think is a perfectly valid discussion, but I think he posed it on too narrow a front, and not thinking enough about, for instance, about production, mechanised production in China, and to some extent, in India, within the cloth trade
. But at the back of my mind I\rquote ve always had an interest in the work of Marx and Weber, and I think that\rquote s meant a lot to me. And so too has Perry Anderson\rquote s work, I think. But there have been a lot of things that I\rquote 
ve considered in that way. I\rquote ve never talked to Perry about it, so it\rquote s been mostly reading something that\rquote s sparked things off, rather than discourse.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, that\rquote 
s interesting. And what role has the College played in your life\rquote s work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, it\rquote 
s been a great boon to me, but once again, you know, as a sociologist \endash  I had David Lockwood here at St John\rquote s. In fact, I think I put his name up. But I wouldn\rquote 
t say that David influenced me a great deal in any way, in a sociological direction. Perhaps somebody who did was Talcott Parsons when he was here, but then I had read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The Structure of Social Action}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
 long before he came here. It was much more reading that, and talking about that with people. I used to meet somebody [Melvin Richter] at Oxford, regularly \endash  I think I mentioned this \endash  to talk about a chapter of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 The Structure of Social Action}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667  we used to read \endash 
 I was at Balliol with him, he was a political scientist, but teaching at Hunter College \endash  and he and I used to discuss Parsons\rquote s chapters on Weber and Durkheim and so on, but that wasn\rquote t really Parsons\rquote 
s presence, though I did know him \endash  it was Parsons\rquote s book that I read, that informed me, reading at Oxford at that time. It set the mind in motion about various ideas to do with the East and the West, in that sense, and the Weberian paradig
m, which he didn\rquote t deal with, but which was, to some extent, there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab So you wouldn\rquote 
t really say that the College has been an intellectual home to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, it has been an intellectual home, but it\rquote s not one that I\rquote ve discussed ideas very much with. I\rquote ve discussed a bit with my friend, Robert Hinde, who is here, and another great friend ... (?? \endash 
 52.49) the [mathematical] economist, and through the years I\rquote ve talked to him quite a bit, but mainly it\rquote s been me telling him what I think about development in Africa, for example, rather than anything else. I\rquote 
m sure I could learn a lot, but he\rquote s a mathematical economist, and I don\rquote t understand much about the maths!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Okay. So now, looking over your life\rquote s work as a whole, just two final questions. One is, which aspects of your work do you feel most proud of?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12461627 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, that\rquote s a difficult question, because I\rquote 
m proud of my fieldwork, but I am particularly proud of my work on this myth that I mentioned to you, which I sp
ent such a long time working on, because I think the insight which arose from the myth, into, if you like, [the] primitive oral mentality assumption, is very different from what people supposed it was. And also I\rquote 
ve had the opportunity, through having a tape recorder, to record this myth over some 20 or 30 years, so I\rquote ve been able to show some changes in it. So I think I\rquote 
m able to show that simple societies are not as static as is actually often supposed. There\rquote s much more of freedom goi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12461627 ng on.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But I suppose the thing that\rquote s had more effect has been the stuff I did arising from the work with Ian Watt, on literacy, though nowadays, since I\rquote 
ve just completed this volume on the Renaissances that CUP will publish, which has much more to do with Talcott Parsons. That work, I suppose, I\rquote ve been most proud of. That\rquote 
s the sort of thing I think things have been leading to recently, what with the stuff I did on the difference between Asia and Africa in terms of kinship and other things, and flowers and food, much more 
trying to show that these other societies in Eurasia have been more like Euro}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid12461627 pe than has often been thought.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 I think the present situation in China and India is making my prediction much more valuable than that of Marx or Weber, in that sense! That is to 
say that they are rising at such a rapid rate, which, given their theories, they shouldn\rquote t be doing. They aren\rquote t simply borrowing, they\rquote 
re building on their own as well, and I think that is what is significant there. That is to say they\rquote re building on something which is what Africa can\rquote t do at the moment, can\rquote t do it in the same way. They\rquote 
ll do so eventually, but I think that India and China are certainly building on what they had before. That\rquote s why I enjoyed so much going to Japan, seeing the importance of
 this metallurgy industry. Iron has only been with us since 1000 or 1200, all subsequently, everything, that\rquote 
s moved down from the Iron Age has been from that time, and Japan was basically advanced in metallurgy techniques. So too was China, in terms of br
ass. For instance, brass making very early on in China was with extraordinary complexity. And when you think of the search for metals, directly you\rquote 
ve got the metal ages coming in, in the Bronze Age or the Iron Age, that metals are so unevenly distributed about the earth \endash  as we know only too well from looking at the newspapers about this place and that place \endash 
 that people were forced to go and look for them. So I think this important aspect of getting information around, that you had to search for material
s, Phoenicians coming all that way for tin in Cornwall and so on, you were forced to do that directly you wanted those metals. You couldn\rquote 
t simply stay locked up in Tyre or wherever, or Sidon, you had to go all the way to Cornwall in order to get it. So along the way you passed all these other places \endash  Carthage and so on \endash 
 so I think that was very important in the spread of information in that way.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12876488 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Just one last question. In all those 50 or more years of being an anthropologist, what have been the worst and best experiences?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, in academic life, I don\rquote t know. I find I\rquote ve been extremely fortunate to be able to do what I\rquote ve been able to do in academic life. Personal life, one\rquote 
s had problems, and the problems have been partly from the nature of the fieldwork, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab From the fieldwork?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, with doing fieldwork abroad, which I did, first of all, leaving my family here, and came back to find things rather different. So that was a bit stressful, but after that I can\rquote t think of anything that\rquote 
s been particularly bad. I mean, I\rquote m cheering, on the other hand, the fact that I\rquote ve been able to produce a book at the age of 89!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab That\rquote 
s fantastic! What\rquote s your best experience, do you think, in all that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab I don\rquote 
t really know. I suppose in a conventional way, being elected for a Chair here, perhaps. I don\rquote t frankly know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Paul:}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab 
Well, what about fieldwork? 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri113\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin113\lin1871\itap0\pararsid7808190 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid1191190\charrsid1191190 Jack:}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 \tab Well, I enjoyed fieldwork very much. I en
joyed my fieldwork, especially among the LoWiili, the first one I did, which meant much more to me, and particularly because I had this great friend [Kum] \endash  I showed you his book \endash  and I saw a lot of him, and I think the friendship \endash 
 and I never lost touch
. It must have been very different doing fieldwork in earlier days, where you had such difficulty in getting [there] like Malinowski did, to New Guinea. Whereas by the time I could go, when I went, you could go and you could come back, and go again, and t
he aeroplane made that much easier, so it made the connections much closer. And my friend, Kum, could come and go. And he lived here and so on. And we saw one another very often. And his death was certainly a great loss for me. But then I\rquote 
m sure there have been other losses like that, the loss of colleagues and so on. I was very close to Meyer Fortes, and to Edmund Leach when they were here, so their going was a loss to me.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7808190   }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid677667\charrsid677667 But then there\rquote 
